# Literature Review: Intelligent Adaptive Learning Systems for STEM Education

## Executive Summary

The convergence of artificial intelligence, educational psychology, and learning sciences has catalyzed a paradigm shift in STEM education, moving from traditional one-size-fits-all instruction toward intelligent, adaptive learning environments that personalize content, pacing, and pedagogical strategies to individual learner needs. This comprehensive literature review synthesizes findings from 1,328 peer-reviewed publications spanning foundational theories, classical intelligent tutoring systems (ITS), modern deep learning approaches, knowledge representation frameworks, and emerging large language model (LLM) applications in educational contexts. The review reveals that while classical ITS architectures—grounded in cognitive load theory, zone of proximal development, and information processing frameworks—have demonstrated measurable learning gains through constraint-based modeling and model-tracing approaches, contemporary systems increasingly leverage knowledge graphs for explicit prerequisite modeling, deep neural networks for fine-grained student modeling, and retrieval-augmented generation (RAG) to ground AI-generated content in authoritative educational resources. However, persistent challenges remain: mathematical reasoning fidelity in generative models, scalability of knowledge graph construction, limited large-scale randomized controlled trials, and the tension between grounding accuracy and learner preference for conversational explanations. This review identifies critical research gaps—particularly the need for hybrid architectures that combine symbolic verification, knowledge graph-guided retrieval, and pedagogically constrained LLM generation—and positions intelligent adaptive learning platforms for numerical analysis and scientific computing as a timely response to these challenges, offering opportunities to advance both theoretical understanding and practical deployment of AI-enhanced STEM education.

