## 8. Multi-Modal Learning Environments and Visualization

Effective STEM education often requires multiple representational formats—symbolic notation, graphical visualizations, interactive simulations, and natural language explanations—to support diverse learning preferences and facilitate conceptual understanding. This section examines the role of visualization and multi-modal interaction in adaptive learning systems.

### 8.1 Interactive Visualizations and Manipulatives

Dynamic visualizations and interactive manipulatives enable learners to explore mathematical and scientific concepts through direct manipulation, supporting constructivist learning principles. Luu (2025) developed animation libraries using MANIM for mathematical derivations and acoustics concepts, reporting that targeted animations aided comprehension of dynamic processes and abstract relationships. The animations provided step-by-step visual representations of algebraic manipulations, geometric transformations, and physical phenomena, enabling learners to observe processes that are difficult to convey through static text or images alone.

The effectiveness of visualizations depends critically on their integration with instructional scaffolding. Passive viewing of animations provides limited benefit; active engagement—predicting outcomes, manipulating parameters, explaining observed phenomena—is necessary for deep learning. Adaptive systems can enhance visualization effectiveness by prompting prediction before revealing outcomes, asking learners to explain observed patterns, and adjusting visualization complexity based on learner expertise.

### 8.2 Multi-Representational Workspaces

Multi-representational learning environments present concepts simultaneously in multiple formats—equations, graphs, tables, verbal descriptions—and support coordinated manipulation across representations. Liu et al. (2024) found that multi-representational workspaces combined with adaptive prompts shortened completion time and supported performance improvements in mathematics ITS deployments. The system enabled learners to manipulate algebraic expressions while observing corresponding changes in graphical representations, supporting understanding of relationships between symbolic and visual forms.

Fancsali et al. (2021) documented that engagement nudges and process-oriented prompts in multi-representational mathematics tutors improved engagement with available scaffolds and reduced failure rates. The prompts encouraged learners to use multiple representations strategically—for example, sketching graphs to support algebraic problem-solving or constructing tables to identify patterns—rather than relying exclusively on procedural symbol manipulation.

The design challenge lies in managing cognitive load: multiple simultaneous representations can overwhelm working memory if not carefully coordinated. Effective designs use adaptive scaffolding to introduce representations gradually, provide explicit guidance on when and how to use each representation, and support learners in constructing connections between representational forms.

### 8.3 Computer Vision and Handwriting Recognition

Integrating computer vision capabilities enables tutoring systems to accept handwritten input, photograph-based problem submission, and gesture-based interaction, bridging the gap between traditional paper-based work and digital tutoring systems. Guerino et al. (2025) developed MathAIde, a teacher-centered system with photo-based exercise correction, emphasizing mixed-methods evaluation to improve classroom adoption in resource-limited settings. The system allows students to photograph handwritten solutions, uses computer vision to extract mathematical expressions, and provides automated feedback on correctness and common errors.

The approach addresses a practical barrier to ITS adoption: many students, particularly in resource-limited contexts, prefer or require paper-based work. By accepting photographed solutions, systems can provide automated feedback without requiring students to learn specialized input interfaces or abandon familiar work practices. However, handwriting recognition for mathematical notation remains challenging due to variability in notation, ambiguous symbols, and two-dimensional layout. Current systems achieve acceptable accuracy for printed or carefully handwritten expressions but struggle with cursive writing, non-standard notation, and complex layouts.

The integration of multi-modal input and output—text, speech, handwriting, visualization—represents an important direction for inclusive, accessible adaptive learning systems. However, each modality introduces technical challenges and potential failure modes that must be carefully managed through robust error handling, user feedback mechanisms, and graceful degradation when recognition fails.

