## 11. Conclusion

This comprehensive literature review has synthesized findings from 1,328 peer-reviewed publications spanning foundational learning theories, classical and modern intelligent tutoring systems, knowledge representation frameworks, student modeling approaches, large language model applications, and integrated adaptive learning platforms. The review reveals a field in transition: classical ITS architectures grounded in cognitive theory and explicit domain models are being augmented—and in some cases replaced—by data-driven, neural approaches that offer greater scalability and flexibility but introduce new challenges related to interpretability, mathematical fidelity, and pedagogical alignment.

Several key themes emerge from this synthesis. First, theoretical foundations—cognitive load theory, zone of proximal development, information processing, and self-regulated learning frameworks—provide essential design principles that remain relevant despite technological evolution. Successful adaptive systems navigate inherent tensions between these frameworks through context-sensitive design, real-time student modeling, and empirical validation. Second, the evolution from rule-based tutors to hybrid architectures reflects a broader trend toward combining symbolic and statistical approaches, leveraging explicit pedagogical knowledge where available while using data-driven methods to handle variability and reduce authoring costs. Third, knowledge graphs and ontologies enable interpretable sequencing and transparent recommendation, addressing limitations of opaque embedding spaces and supporting curricular alignment. Fourth, student modeling has progressed from simple probabilistic trackers to sophisticated neural architectures, but the field must prioritize diagnostic validity and learning outcomes over predictive accuracy alone. Fifth, large language models introduce powerful natural language capabilities but require verification layers, grounding mechanisms, and pedagogical scaffolding to ensure mathematical correctness and instructional coherence. Sixth, retrieval-augmented generation offers a promising approach to ground AI-generated content in authoritative resources, though trade-offs between grounding accuracy and human preference require careful navigation.

Critical research gaps persist across methodological, technical, and practical dimensions. Methodologically, the field requires large-scale randomized controlled trials measuring learning outcomes rather than only predictive accuracy, standardized benchmarks enabling fair cross-study comparisons, and greater attention to equity, accessibility, and deployment in under-resourced contexts. Technically, achieving reliable mathematical reasoning in generative models, scaling knowledge graph construction, balancing interpretability and expressiveness in student models, and resolving grounding-preference trade-offs remain open challenges. Practically, addressing infrastructure constraints, supporting teacher professional development, ensuring privacy and ethical data use, and demonstrating long-term effectiveness and sustainability are essential for widespread adoption.

The proposed research on intelligent adaptive learning platforms for numerical analysis and scientific computing is well-positioned to address these gaps through hybrid architectures that combine knowledge graph-guided retrieval, verifier-augmented LLM generation, and interpretable student modeling. By integrating explicit prerequisite structures with data-driven personalization, symbolic verification with natural language generation, and teacher-in-the-loop design with automated adaptation, such platforms can advance both theoretical understanding and practical deployment of AI-enhanced STEM education. However, success requires not only technical innovation but also rigorous evaluation, educator collaboration, and sustained attention to equity and accessibility. The convergence of educational theory, knowledge representation, deep learning, and generative AI creates unprecedented opportunities to realize the long-standing vision of personalized, effective, scalable STEM education—but only if the field addresses identified gaps with methodological rigor, technical sophistication, and ethical responsibility.

